# Report System — Frontend

React-based dashboard for the Oracle Report System. Connects to a Spring Boot backend, provides folder-based report navigation, scheduled report management, execution logs, and real-time WebSocket notifications.

---

## Tech Stack

- **React 18** with Vite
- **Inline styles** (no CSS framework)
- **WebSocket** for real-time notifications
- REST API via centralized `api.js` utility

---

## Prerequisites

- Node.js 18+
- Backend running at `http://localhost:8080` (or configure via `.env`)

---

## Getting Started

```bash
# Install dependencies
npm install

# Start development server
npm run dev
```

App will be available at `http://localhost:5173`

---

## Corporate / Restricted Network

If you are behind a corporate proxy:

```bash
npm config set proxy http://ip_address:port
npm config set https-proxy http://ip_address:port
```

To unset proxy later:

```bash
npm config delete proxy
npm config delete https-proxy
```

---

## Environment Variables

Create a `.env` file in the project root:

```env
VITE_API_BASE=http://localhost:8080
```

For production:

```env
# .env.production
VITE_API_BASE=http://your-server-ip:8081
```

> Vite embeds these at build time — always rebuild after changing `.env.production`.

---

## Build for Production

```bash
npm run build
```

Output goes to `dist/`. Serve it with Nginx or any static file server.

**Nginx example:**

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    root /var/www/report-system/dist;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }

    location /api/ {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8080;
    }

    location /ws/ {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8080;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection "upgrade";
    }
}
```

---

## Project Structure

```
src/
  api.js                  — Centralized fetch utility (auth headers, base URL)
  App.jsx                 — Root: auth guard, Login / Dashboard routing
  Dashboard.jsx           — Shell: sidebar, topbar, page routing, WS notifications
  useNotifications.js     — WebSocket hook (auto-reconnect, ping/pong)
  pushNotification.js     — Browser Notification permission helper
  pages/
    GenerateReportPage.jsx — Folder grid → report list → run / schedule
    ScheduledLogsPage.jsx  — Scheduled report history, toggle, delete
    LogsPage.jsx           — Execution logs with pagination
    UsersPage.jsx          — User management (admin only)
    ReportsPage.jsx        — Report–user access assignment (admin only)
```

---

## Authentication

JWT token is stored in `localStorage`. All requests include:

```
Authorization: Bearer <token>
```

WebSocket connection passes the token as a query parameter:

```
ws://host/ws/notifications?token=<jwt>
```

---

## Real-time Notifications

When a scheduled report finishes (success or error), a toast notification appears in the bottom-right corner. The WebSocket connection is established automatically on login and reconnects every 5 seconds if dropped.

No external push service required — works entirely through the backend WebSocket endpoint.

---

## Key Design Decisions

**Why no state management library?**
All state is local to components or lifted one level. The app has no cross-cutting shared state that would justify Redux or Zustand overhead.

**Why inline styles?**
Zero build-time CSS dependencies, no class name collisions, styles are co-located with components. Trade-off is verbosity, which is acceptable at this scale.

**Why WebSocket over FCM/Web Push?**
The backend runs in a network-restricted environment without outbound internet access. WebSocket requires no external services and works reliably on localhost and intranet deployments.

**Why `VITE_API_BASE` instead of hardcoding?**
Allows the same build artifact to be deployed to different environments by only changing environment files, without touching source code.
